        {
            "title": "Resource Governance and Developmental States: Critical International Political Economy Perspectives",
            "date": {
                "start": {
                    "month": 11,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2011
                },
                "end": {
                    "month": 11,
                    "day": null,
                    "year": 2013
                }
            },
            "description": "Resource Governance and Developmental States in the Global South explores the extent to which neoliberalism as a global political project has both constrained and opened opportunities for economic development in the developing world. Using the framework of critical international political economy (IPE), we challenge the long held views about the ways natural resources shape political and economic outcomes. The authors examine how the specific feature of the resource sector creates different dynamics of policy change, and therefore, the range of development options for the Global South move beyond adopting unregulated, open extractive markets. The collection offers a robust engagement with development theory and political economy literature by exploring the ideational construction, implementation, and subsequent recalibration of mining reforms in the last three decades across the Global South. In many ways, our contribution lies in our attempts at unpacking neoliberalism as a singular process of reforming minerals and oil sectors in different geographical contexts. By placing distinctive national experiences in multiple layers of authority at local, national and international levels, the collection likewise demonstrates how differing national governance styles are embedded in \u2013 and constrained by \u2013 the twin logics of global competitiveness and privatisation. Finally, our sustained emphasis on the role of states in governing resources make clear the authors\u2019 commitment to the challenges and limitations of constructing developmental states in the era of emerging markets. In so doing, the book principally explores the theory and praxis of neoliberalism in the Global South, as articulated in strategic extractive industries, by way of examining the tensions, contradictions, and attempts at reconstructing the coherence of (neoliberal) mining management. ",
