                    "year": 2012
                }
            },
            "description": "This is a comparative research on the political economy of development in Brazil and Chile, investigating how states develop export-oriented growth policies through their natural resource sectors. While most studies in the field focus on the politics of mineral rents, the project explores the role of state-owned enterprises in facilitating growth strategies. It examines the central role of state-building in development and the ways natural resources were managed through different kinds of state-oriented policies. I look at the oil and mining reforms in the past three decades (1980s-2000s) and show how SOEs played a role in making these industries competitive. It concludes by looking at the challenge of how to effective govern the sector in the era of low commodity prices.",
